 <h4>Verify Input Method</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>Ensure you are using a bare finger or approved stylus; other objects may not register.</li>
   <li><em>Why:</em> The B450 touchscreen is capacitive and may not respond to non-approved objects.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h4>Check Display and Calibration Settings</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>Navigate (if possible via physical buttons) to touchscreen calibration settings and re-calibrate.</li>
   <li><em>Why:</em> Miscalibration can make the touchscreen appear unresponsive or inaccurate.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h4>Environmental Check</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>Confirm the monitor is not exposed to excessive heat, moisture, or magnetic interference.</li>
   <li><em>Why:</em> Environmental conditions can affect touchscreen sensitivity.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h4>Test with External Interface (if available)</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>If the monitor supports external input (mouse or keyboard), test responsiveness.</li>
   <li><em>Why:</em> Determines if the issue is software-related or strictly touchscreen hardware.</li>
 </ul>
 
-<h4>If the Problem Persists</h4>
+<h2>If the Problem Persists</h2>
 <ul>
   <li>Common external causes have been ruled out; the touchscreen or internal display controller may be failing.</li>
   <li>Action: Remove monitor from service. Label “Out of Service.” Send to Biomedical Engineering or vendor repair.</li>
   <li>Note: Knowing when to escalate is proper troubleshooting.</li>
 </ul>
 
-<h4>Clinical Use Tip</h4>
+<h2>Clinical Use Tip</h2>
 <ul>
   <li>Do not troubleshoot on an active patient. Move patient monitoring to a backup device before any troubleshooting.</li>
   <li>Only interact with the touchscreen when the monitor is safely offline.</li>
 </ul>
 
-<h4>Work Order Documentation (CCR Method)</h4>
-<ul>
-  <li><strong>Complaint:</strong> “Touchscreen not responding during routine patient monitoring.”</li>
-  <li><strong>Cause:</strong> “Monitor touchscreen remained unresponsive after confirming power, cleaning, and restarting the device.”</li>
-  <li><strong>Resolution:</strong> “Monitor removed from service, labeled Out of Service, and sent for vendor evaluation.”</li>
-</ul>
+<h2>Work Order Documentation (CCR Method)</h2>
+
+<h4>Complaint</h4>
+<p>What was reported by the clinical staff.</p>
+<p><em>Example:</em><br>
+“Touchscreen not responding during routine patient monitoring.”</p>
+
+<h4>Cause</h4>
+<p>What was observed during troubleshooting.</p>
+<p><em>Example:</em><br>
+“Monitor touchscreen remained unresponsive after confirming power, cleaning, and restarting the device.”</p>
+
+<h4>Resolution</h4>
+<p>What action was taken.</p>
+<p><em>Example:</em><br>
+“Monitor removed from service, labeled Out of Service, and sent for vendor evaluation.”</p>
 
-<h4>Helpful Details to Include</h4>
+<h2>Helpful Details to Include (If Known)</h2>
 <ul>
   <li>Outlet tested and verified</li>
   <li>AC adapter or battery checked</li>
   <li>Screen cleaned and verified</li>
   <li>Monitor power-cycled</li>
   <li>Calibration attempted</li>
   <li>Environmental conditions noted</li>
   <li>Monitor removed from patient use</li>
 </ul>
 
 <p><strong>That is successful troubleshooting.</strong></p>
 
