 <section class="hero">
   <h2>GE CARESCAPE B850</h2>
   <p>Power Issue – Will Not Turn On</p>
 </section>
 
 <main style="max-width: 900px; margin: 40px auto; padding: 0 20px;">
   <h3>Asset Type</h3>
   <p>Patient Monitor</p>
   
   <h3>Manufacturer</h3>
   <p>GE Healthcare</p>
   
   <h3>Model</h3>
   <p>B850</p>
   
   
-  <h3>What This Guide Helps With</h3>
+  <h2>What This Guide Helps With</h2>
   <p>This guide provides a structured Clinical Engineering approach when a CARESCAPE B850 monitor will not power on.</p>
   <p>The focus is on logical, external, and easily verifiable checks before assuming internal failure. These steps rule out common power-related causes while maintaining patient safety and minimizing unnecessary escalation.</p>
   
-  <h3>Step-by-Step Troubleshooting</h3>
+  <h2>Step-by-Step Troubleshooting</h2>
   
   <h4>Ensure Patient Safety First</h4>
   <ul>
     <li>If the monitor is in clinical use: transfer the patient to a functioning monitor first.</li>
     <li>Do not troubleshoot while the monitor is actively required for patient care.</li>
     <li>Confirm the device is safe to remove from service before proceeding.</li>
   </ul>
   
   <h4>Verify AC Power at the Outlet</h4>
   <ul>
     <li>Confirm the monitor is connected to a known-working hospital-grade outlet.</li>
     <li>Test the outlet with a known-good device (lamp, outlet tester, etc.).</li>
     <li>If plugged into a power strip, isolation transformer, or UPS, verify that device is powered on and functioning.</li>
     <li>If available, try a different known-working wall outlet.</li>
     <li><em>Why this matters: Loss of upstream power is the most common and simplest cause of a “dead” monitor.</em></li>
   </ul>
   
   <h4>Inspect and Reseat the Power Cord</h4>
   <ul>
     <li>Visually inspect the power cord for cuts, fraying, bent or damaged prongs, and loose connector ends.</li>
     <li>Reseat the cord firmly at the wall outlet and the rear AC inlet of the monitor.</li>
     <li>If available, swap with a known-good hospital-grade power cord and attempt to power on again.</li>
     <li><em>Why this matters: A loose or internally failed cord can mimic total device failure.</em></li>
   </ul>
   
   <h4>Confirm the Rear Power Switch Position</h4>
   <ul>
     <li>Verify the rear power rocker switch is in the ON position.</li>
     <li>Then press the front power button.</li>
     <li>Do not assume the switch position without physically checking it.</li>
   </ul>
   
   <h4>Observe for Any Signs of Activity</h4>
   <ul>
     <li>When attempting to power on, closely observe front LED indicators, brief screen flash, audible fan noise, or clicking sounds.</li>
     <li>Even minimal activity suggests partial power presence and helps narrow down whether the failure is complete or localized.</li>
   </ul>
   
-  <h4>If the Problem Persists</h4>
+  <h2>If the Problem Persists</h2>
   <ul>
     <li>If the monitor shows no indicator lights, no fan noise, no display activity, and no response with known-good outlet and power cord, then common external causes have been ruled out.</li>
     <li>At this point, the issue is likely internal (power supply board, internal fuse, or power distribution failure).</li>
     <li>Remove the monitor from service, label clearly as Out of Service, and send for repair or bench evaluation.</li>
     <li>Knowing when to stop prevents unnecessary downtime and protects patient safety. Escalation after logical checks is proper troubleshooting.</li>
   </ul>
   
-  <h4>Clinical Use Tip</h4>
+  <h2>Clinical Use Tip</h2>
   <ul>
     <li>Never troubleshoot a non-powering monitor on an active patient.</li>
     <li>Always move the patient to a working monitor first, confirm monitoring continuity, then remove the failed unit from service.</li>
     <li>Patient monitoring continuity takes priority over equipment evaluation.</li>
   </ul>
   
-  <h4>Work Order Documentation (CCR Method)</h4>
+  <h2>Work Order Documentation (CCR Method)</h2>
   
   <h4>Complaint</h4>
-  <p>What was reported. Example: “Monitor will not power on.”</p>
+<p>What was reported by the clinical staff.</p>
+<p><em>Example:</em><br>
+“Monitor will not power on.”</p>
   
   <h4>Cause</h4>
-  <p>What was observed during troubleshooting. Example: “Unit does not power on with known-working outlet and known-good power cord. Rear switch verified ON. No indicator lights, fan noise, or display activity observed. Suspected internal power supply failure.”</p>
+<p>What was observed during troubleshooting.</p>
+<p><em>Example:</em><br>
+“Unit does not power on with known-working outlet and known-good power cord. Rear switch verified ON. No indicator lights, fan noise, or display activity observed. Suspected internal power supply failure.”</p>
   
   <h4>Resolution</h4>
-  <p>What action was taken. Examples: “Removed from service and tagged Out of Service.”, “Sent to Biomed shop for bench evaluation.”, “Dispatched for vendor repair.”</p>
+<p>What action was taken.</p>
+<p><em>Example:</em><br>
+“Removed from service and tagged Out of Service.”, “Sent to Biomed shop for bench evaluation.”, “Dispatched for vendor repair.”</p>
   
-  <h4>Helpful Details to Include (If Known)</h4>
+  <h2>Helpful Details to Include (If Known)</h2>
   <ul>
     <li>Outlet tested (yes/no)</li>
     <li>Alternate outlet attempted</li>
     <li>Power cord swapped (yes/no)</li>
     <li>Rear switch position confirmed</li>
     <li>Indicator light behavior</li>
     <li>Fan noise present/absent</li>
     <li>Any unusual odor or heat</li>
     <li>Final device status (returned to service or sent for repair)</li>
   </ul>
   
-  <h4>Final Thought</h4>
+  <h2>Final Thought</h2>
   <p>Effective troubleshooting starts with the simplest external checks and progresses logically. Ruling out power source and connection issues protects patient safety, reduces unnecessary part replacement, and supports accurate repair escalation.</p>
   <p>A Clinical Engineer’s role is not just to fix equipment — it is to think systematically, document clearly, and know when escalation is appropriate.</p>
   
   <p><strong>That is successful troubleshooting.</strong></p>
   
   </main>
   
