--- a/guides/ge-mac-vu360-printer.html
+++ b/guides/ge-mac-vu360-printer.html
@@ -99,51 +99,51 @@
 <li>Review the display for printer-related error codes.</li>
 <li>Document exact wording of the message.</li>
 <li>Do not attempt board-level repair based on codes; this is for documentation and escalation.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h2>If the Problem Persists</h2>
 <p>If the printer still does not function after verifying settings, paper supply, density, cleaning, and performing a self-test, common external causes have been ruled out.</p>
 
 <p>The issue is likely internal (thermal print head, feed motor, internal printer assembly, or connection issue).</p>
 
 <ul>
 <li>Remove the device from clinical service</li>
 <li>Label it Out of Service</li>
 <li>Send the unit for bench evaluation or authorized repair</li>
 </ul>
 
 <p>Knowing when to stop prevents unnecessary downtime and protects equipment integrity.</p>
 
 <h2>Clinical Use Tip</h2>
 <p>Never troubleshoot printer components while a patient is actively being tested. If documentation is urgently needed, move the patient to another ECG machine and complete the study there. Troubleshooting should only occur when patient care is not impacted.</p>
 
 <h2>Work Order Documentation (CCR Method)</h2>
 
 <h4>Complaint</h4>
 <p>What was reported by the clinical staff.</p>
-<p><em>Example:</em><br>
+<p><em>Example:</em><br>
 “ECG prints blank pages.”<br>
 or<br>
 “Printout is very faint and unreadable.”</p>
 
 <h4>Cause</h4>
