+<h2>What This Guide Helps With</h2>
 <p>This guide provides a structured Clinical Engineering approach when a Verathon Prime Plus bladder scanner exhibits touchscreen or display issues. The focus is on simple, external checks that are most commonly associated with display problems, such as power, connections, or screen contamination, before assuming internal failure.</p>
 <p>These steps prioritize patient safety, proper escalation, and accurate CCR documentation.</p>
 
 <h4>Power Check</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>Confirm the device is fully charged or connected to AC power.</li>
   <li>Verify the battery status indicator is normal.</li>
   <li><em>Why:</em> A low battery or intermittent power can cause touchscreen responsiveness issues or blank screens.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h4>Inspect Cables and Connectors</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>Check for loose or damaged AC adapters, docking station connectors, and probe connections.</li>
   <li>Re-seat all cables securely.</li>
   <li><em>Why:</em> Loose connections can prevent the display from initializing correctly.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h4>Clean the Touchscreen</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>Use a soft, lint-free cloth dampened with water or approved screen cleaner.</li>
   <li>Avoid abrasive materials or excessive moisture.</li>
   <li><em>Why:</em> Oils, dirt, or debris can block touch input or create ghost touches.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h4>Restart the Device</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>Power off completely, wait 10–15 seconds, then power on.</li>
   <li>Observe the display during boot for abnormalities.</li>
   <li><em>Why:</em> Temporary software glitches often resolve with a restart.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h4>Check for Physical Damage</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>Inspect the touchscreen for cracks, deep scratches, or liquid ingress.</li>
   <li><em>Why:</em> Physical damage can permanently affect touchscreen performance or display visibility.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h4>Test in Alternate Settings</h4>
 <ul>
