   <li>If expired, replace with in-date pads and retest.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h4>Test With a Known-Good Cable or Pad Set</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>If available:</li>
   <li>Replace pads with a known-good set.</li>
   <li>If the issue persists, replace the therapy cable with a known-good cable.</li>
   <li>This step isolates whether the problem follows the pads, the cable, or remains with the defibrillator.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h4>Observe the Exact Display Message</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>Document:</li>
   <li>Exact wording of the error</li>
   <li>Whether the message appears immediately on power-up</li>
   <li>Whether it is intermittent</li>
   <li>Any audible tones or status indicators</li>
 </ul>
 <p>Precise messaging helps determine if the issue is cable-related versus internal therapy board failure.</p>
 
-<h4>If the Problem Persists</h4>
+<h2>If the Problem Persists</h2>
 <p>If the device continues to report “Pads Not Detected” or “Therapy Cable Failure” after:</p>
 <ul>
   <li>Reseating connections</li>
   <li>Inspecting for damage</li>
   <li>Replacing pads</li>
   <li>Testing with a known-good cable</li>
 </ul>
 <p>Then common external causes have been ruled out.</p>
 
 <p>Next steps:</p>
 <ul>
   <li>Remove the device from clinical service</li>
   <li>Label the unit Out of Service</li>
   <li>Send for bench evaluation or authorized repair</li>
 </ul>
 
 <p>Do not continue repeated cycling or troubleshooting beyond external checks. Knowing when to stop is proper Clinical Engineering practice.</p>
 
-<h4>Clinical Use Tip</h4>
+<h2>Clinical Use Tip</h2>
 <p>Never troubleshoot pad detection issues on an active patient.</p>
 
 <p>If the unit is in clinical use:</p>
 <ul>
   <li>Immediately transfer the patient to a backup defibrillator.</li>
   <li>Ensure therapy capability is restored before beginning equipment evaluation.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <p>Pad detection errors prevent reliable therapy delivery. Device readiness is critical in resuscitation environments.</p>
 
-<h3>Work Order Documentation (CCR Method)</h3>
+<h2>Work Order Documentation (CCR Method)</h2>
 <p>CCR = Complaint, Cause, Resolution</p>
 
 <h4>Complaint</h4>
-<p>Example:<br>
-“R Series defibrillator displays ‘Pads Not Detected’ during daily check.”</p>
+<p>What was reported by the clinical staff.</p>
+<p><em>Example:</em><br>
+<br> “R Series defibrillator displays ‘Pads Not Detected’ during daily check.”</p>
 
 <h4>Cause</h4>
-<p>Examples:<br>
-“Therapy cable intermittently loses connection when flexed near strain relief.”<br>
-or<br>
-“Pads expired and not recognized by device.”<br>
-or<br>
-“No issue found with pads or cable; suspected internal therapy board fault.”</p>
+<p>What was observed during troubleshooting.</p>
+<p><em>Example:</em><br>
+<br> “Therapy cable intermittently loses connection when flexed near strain relief.”<br> or<br> “Pads expired and not recognized by device.”<br> or<br> “No issue found with pads or cable; suspected internal therapy board fault.”</p>
 
 <h4>Resolution</h4>
-<p>Examples:<br>
-“Replaced expired pads; unit passed operational check and returned to service.”<br>
-“Removed defective therapy cable from service and replaced with known-good cable.”<br>
-“Unit removed from service and sent to vendor for evaluation.”</p>
+<p>What action was taken.</p>
+<p><em>Example:</em><br>
+<br> “Replaced expired pads; unit passed operational check and returned to service.”<br> “Removed defective therapy cable from service and replaced with known-good cable.”<br> “Unit removed from service and sent to vendor for evaluation.”</p>
 
-<h3>Helpful Details to Include (If Known)</h3>
+<h2>Helpful Details to Include (If Known)</h2>
 <ul>
   <li>Pads reseated: yes / no</li>
   <li>Therapy cable reseated: yes / no</li>
   <li>Visible damage observed: yes / no</li>
   <li>Known-good pads tested: yes / no</li>
   <li>Known-good cable tested: yes / no</li>
