   <h2>ZOLL R Series Defibrillator</h2>
   <p>Printer Not Printing / Paper Jam (Thermal Paper)</p>
 </section>
 
 <main style="max-width: 900px; margin: 40px auto; padding: 0 20px;">
 
 <h3>Asset Type</h3>
 <p>Defibrillator</p>
 
 <h3>Manufacturer</h3>
 <p>ZOLL</p>
 
 <h3>Model</h3>
 <p>R Series</p>
 
-<h3>What This Guide Helps With</h3>
+<h2>What This Guide Helps With</h2>
 
 <p>This guide provides a structured Clinical Engineering approach when a ZOLL R Series defibrillator printer will not print or displays a paper jam message.</p>
 
 <p>The R Series uses thermal paper, which is sensitive to heat, pressure, and handling. Many printer issues are related to paper condition, loading, or feed alignment rather than internal printer failure.</p>
 
 <p>This guide focuses on logical, external checks before assuming a failed printer mechanism.</p>
 
-<h3>Step-by-Step Troubleshooting</h3>
+<h2>Step-by-Step Troubleshooting</h2>
 
 <h4>1. Ensure Patient Safety First</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>Do not troubleshoot on an active code or patient.</li>
   <li>If the device is in clinical use, move the patient to another defibrillator before proceeding.</li>
   <li>Patient care always takes priority over equipment troubleshooting.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h4>2. Check the Paper Stack</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>Open the printer compartment.</li>
   <li>Confirm a paper stack is present.</li>
   <li>Ensure the stack is properly seated and aligned in the tray.</li>
   <li>Verify the top sheet’s leading edge is correctly positioned in the feed path.</li>
   <li>Replace the stack if:
     <ul>
       <li>It is empty</li>
       <li>Edges are curled or bent</li>
       <li>Sheets are wrinkled or compressed</li>
       <li>Paper appears old or heat-damaged</li>
     </ul>
   </li>
   <li>Thermal paper that is creased or compressed can misfeed and trigger jam errors.</li>
 </ul>
 
@@ -88,130 +88,127 @@
   <li>Close the printer cover firmly.</li>
   <li>Listen and feel for the latch click.</li>
   <li>Confirm the cover sits flush and does not spring open.</li>
   <li>A partially latched cover can generate false jam or “Insert Paper” messages.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h4>5. Try a Known-Good Thermal Paper Stack</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>If available:</li>
   <li>Replace the current paper stack with a new, known-good thermal stack.</li>
   <li>Ensure it is the correct type for the R Series.</li>
   <li>Perform a test strip or print an event summary.</li>
   <li>This step helps rule out paper quality issues.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <h4>6. Observe and Record the Exact Display Message</h4>
 <ul>
   <li>Document the exact error shown:</li>
   <li>“Paper Jam”</li>
   <li>“Insert Paper”</li>
   <li>“Printer Error”</li>
   <li>No error, but no print output</li>
   <li>Precise wording is important for trending and repair diagnostics.</li>
 </ul>
 
-<h3>If the Problem Persists</h3>
+<h2>If the Problem Persists</h2>
 
 <p>If the printer still fails after:</p>
 
 <ul>
   <li>Confirming proper paper loading</li>
   <li>Clearing all jams</li>
   <li>Verifying full cover closure</li>
   <li>Trying known-good thermal paper</li>
 </ul>
 
 <p>Then common external causes have been ruled out.</p>
 
 <p>The issue is likely internal, such as:</p>
 
 <ul>
   <li>Thermal print head failure</li>
   <li>Feed motor malfunction</li>
   <li>Sensor failure</li>
   <li>Internal gear damage</li>
 </ul>
 
 <ul>
   <li>Remove the defibrillator from service if printing capability is required per policy.</li>
   <li>Apply an Out of Service label.</li>
   <li>Send for bench evaluation or vendor repair.</li>
 </ul>
 
 <p>Knowing when to stop prevents unnecessary internal damage and protects patient safety.</p>
 
-<h3>Clinical Use Tip</h3>
+<h2>Clinical Use Tip</h2>
 
 <p>Printing during a code event is often required for documentation. If the printer is nonfunctional:</p>
 
 <ul>
   <li>Immediately swap to another defibrillator if documentation printing is required.</li>
   <li>Do not delay patient care while troubleshooting.</li>
   <li>Always verify printer function during PMs and readiness checks to prevent in-service failures.</li>
 </ul>
 
